(70, 1, '2010-09-22 18:18:57', '2010-09-22 18:18:57', 'There is music and a choir at the 10am service. We choose a wide variety of modern and classical music from <em>The Hymnal 1982, Renew</em>, and<em> Lift Every Voice and Sing</em>.We a\n\nAdditionally, we present a children''s christmas concert during Advent.\n\nIf you would like to join the choir, you are invited to show up at practice on Thursday nights at 7:30.', 'What do you do for music?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '68-autosave', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:18:57', '2010-09-22 18:18:57', '', 68, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch.com/archives/70', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(73, 1, '2010-09-22 18:17:50', '2010-09-22 18:17:50', '<p>There is music and a choir at the 10am service. We choose a wide variety of modern and classical music from</p>\r\n<ul>\r\nThe Hymnal 1982</ul>\r\n<p>,</p>\r\n<ul>Renew</ul>\r\n<p>, and</p>\r\n<ul>Lift Every Voice and Sing</ul>\r\n<p>. </p>\r\n<p>Additionally, we present a children''s christmas concert during Advent.</p>\r\n<p>If you would like to join the choir, you are invited to show up at practice on Thursday nights at 7:30.</p>\r\n', 'What do you do for music?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '68-revision-4', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:17:50', '2010-09-22 18:17:50', '', 68, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch.com/archives/73', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(71, 1, '2010-09-22 18:16:53', '2010-09-22 18:16:53', 'There is music and a choir at the 10am service. We choose a wide variety of modern and classical music from <ul>\r\nThe Hymnal 1982</ul>, <ul>Renew</ul>, and <ul>Lift Every Voice and Sing</ul>. \r\n\r\nAdditionally, we present a children''s christmas concert during Advent.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to join the choir, you are invited to show up at practice on Thursday nights at 7:30.\r\n\r\n', 'What do you do for music?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '68-revision-2', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:16:53', '2010-09-22 18:16:53', '', 68, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch.com/archives/71', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(72, 1, '2010-09-22 18:17:31', '2010-09-22 18:17:31', '<p>There is music and a choir at the 10am service. We choose a wide variety of modern and classical music from\r\n<ul>\r\nThe Hymnal 1982</ul>\r\n<p>,\r\n<ul>Renew</ul>\r\n<p>, and\r\n<ul>Lift Every Voice and Sing</ul>\r\n<p>. </p>\r\n<p>Additionally, we present a children''s christmas concert during Advent.</p>\r\n<p>If you would like to join the choir, you are invited to show up at practice on Thursday nights at 7:30.</p>\r\n', 'What do you do for music?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '68-revision-3', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:17:31', '2010-09-22 18:17:31', '', 68, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch.com/archives/72', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(74, 1, '2010-09-22 18:26:21', '2010-09-22 18:26:21', 'Church of Our Redeemer conducts services according the (episcopal) <em>1979 Book of Common Prayer</em> in a ''low church'' style. If you grew up in an Anglican tradition, the forms will be familiar.  If like many of us in the church, however, you didn''t, here''s a few hints.\r\n\r\n1.The entire service is printed in the bulletin each week, and for the most part, you just follow along. Whenever the bulletin says, ''People,'' you read off what it says :)\r\n\r\n2. The order of service usually compromises the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>an opening prayer and song</li>\r\n	<li>readings from the Old Testament, the Psalms, the Epistles, and a reading from the Gospels (during which we typically stand)</li>\r\n	<li>a sermon,usually about 20 minutes or so</li>\r\n	<li>a time of creedal affirmation and prayer</li>\r\n	<li>a time of "Peace" in which we greet one another</li>\r\n	<li>a time of Eucharist (Communion) in which we celebrate the Lord''s Last Supper</li>\r\n	<li>and coffee hour, in which we fellowship with our church</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n3. What if I get lost in the service?\r\n\r\nDon''t worry, we all do. Just peek over at your neighbor, and they''ll help you out.', 'What should I expect in a service at Church of Our Redeemer?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'what-should-i-expect-in-a-service-at-church-of-our-redeemer', '', '', '2010-09-24 15:02:49', '2010-09-24 15:02:49', '', 0, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch.com/?p=74', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(75, 1, '2010-09-22 18:26:11', '2010-09-22 18:26:11', 'Church of Our Redeemer conducts services according the (episcopal) <em>1979 Book of Common Prayer</em> in a ''low church'' style. If you grew up in an Anglican tradition, the forms will be familiar.  If like many of us in the church, however, you didn''t, here''s a few hints.\n\n1.The entire service is printed in the bulletin each week, and for the most part, you just follow along. Whenever the bulletin says, ''People,'' you read off what it says :)\n\n2. The order of service usually compromises the following:\n<ul>\n	<li>an opening prayer and song</li>\n	<li>readings from the Old Testament, the Psalms, the Epistles, and a reading from the Gospels (during which we typically stand)</li>\n	<li>a sermon,usually about 20 minutes or so</li>\n	<li>a time of creedal affirmation and prayer</li>\n	<li>a time of "Peace" in which we greet one another</li>\n	<li>a time of Eucharist (Communion) in which we celebrate the Lord''s Last Supper</li>\n	<li>and coffee hour, in which we fellowship with our church</li>\n</ul>\n3. What if I get lost in the service?  Don''t worry, we all do. Just peek over at your neighbor, and they''ll help you out.', 'What should I expect in a service at Church of Our Redeemer', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '74-revision', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:26:11', '2010-09-22 18:26:11', '', 74, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch.com/archives/75', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(76, 1, '2010-09-22 18:26:21', '2010-09-22 18:26:21', 'Church of Our Redeemer conducts services according the (episcopal) <em>1979 Book of Common Prayer</em> in a ''low church'' style. If you grew up in an Anglican tradition, the forms will be familiar.  If like many of us in the church, however, you didn''t, here''s a few hints.\r\n\r\n1.The entire service is printed in the bulletin each week, and for the most part, you just follow along. Whenever the bulletin says, ''People,'' you read off what it says :)\r\n\r\n2. The order of service usually compromises the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>an opening prayer and song</li>\r\n	<li>readings from the Old Testament, the Psalms, the Epistles, and a reading from the Gospels (during which we typically stand)</li>\r\n	<li>a sermon,usually about 20 minutes or so</li>\r\n	<li>a time of creedal affirmation and prayer</li>\r\n	<li>a time of "Peace" in which we greet one another</li>\r\n	<li>a time of Eucharist (Communion) in which we celebrate the Lord''s Last Supper</li>\r\n	<li>and coffee hour, in which we fellowship with our church</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n3. What if I get lost in the service?\r\n\r\nDon''t worry, we all do. Just peek over at your neighbor, and they''ll help you out.', 'What should I expect in a service at Church of Our Redeemer', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '74-revision-2', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:26:21', '2010-09-22 18:26:21', '', 74, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch.com/archives/76', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(77, 1, '2010-09-22 18:28:56', '2010-09-22 18:28:56', 'Clothes. We definately recommend clothes at our services. :)\r\n\r\nBeyond that, Church of Our Redeemer is not a stuffy place. We don''t wear hats, and only a few people wear suits. Our rector and the people serving up front wear robes, but only in the service.  We''re not going to judge you by what you wear.\r\n\r\nThat said, some people would like to know how "everybody else dresses." If it''s helpful to say, ''business casual,'' then go with that answer.', 'What should I wear?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'what-should-i-wear', '', '', '2010-09-24 15:02:24', '2010-09-24 15:02:24', '', 0, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch.com/?p=77', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(78, 1, '2010-09-22 18:28:51', '2010-09-22 18:28:51', 'Clothes. We definately recommend clothes at our services. :)\n\nBeyond that, Church of Our Redeemer is not a stuffy place. We don''t wear hats, and only a few people wear suits. Our rector and the people serving up front wear robes, but only in the service.  We''re not going to judge you by what you wear.\n\nThat said, some people would like to know how "everybody else dresses." If it''s helpful to say, ''business casual,'' then go with that answer.', 'What should I wear?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '77-revision', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:28:51', '2010-09-22 18:28:51', '', 77, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch.com/archives/78', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(79, 1, '2010-09-22 18:42:49', '2010-09-22 18:42:49', 'We practice what is called ''Believer''s Communion,'' in which we invite <i>all</i> baptized believers to participate. We don''t care if you''re Episcopalian or Baptist or a Christ-follower with a different denomination label. Basically we figure you''re an adult, and know that this is a solemn ceremony memorializing the sacrifice that Jesus made on our behalf. For that reason, both we and <a href="http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=1%20Corinthians%2011:27-29&amp;version=NLT">Scripture</a> suggest you not take it lightly, but we do encourage <em>all</em> baptised Christians (regardless of denomination) to join.  Typically, we suggest that younger children should be confirmed (usually around the age of 11 or 12) before actually taking the elements, but again, we trust you to make that decision.\r\n\r\nIf for any reason you are not comfortable taking communion, please come forward anyway to receive a blessing. If you are concerned about catching anything, you needn''t - our priest uses rubbing alcohol to clean his hands before serving, and the vessels are thoroughly washed after every service.  Finally, if you would prefer, a separate cup for continction (dipping) is available.\r\n\r\n<em><em>So, what is communion?</em></em> If you were observing it like an anthropologist, this is what you''d see:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The Priest pours a cup of wine and prays over a piece of bread.</li>\r\n	<li>Everybody in the church will get out of their seats (by rows), and stand in line until there is space available to kneel at the altar.</li>\r\n	<li>When you get to the altar, if you do NOT want to take the elements, simply cross your hands over your chest, and the priest will give you a blessing. You can simply leave at this point.</li>\r\n	<li>Those receiving communion will hold their hand out for the bread, which the priest will place on the hand. One can either eat the bread or wait until the cup comes and dip it.</li>\r\n	<li>The cup of wine is then brought, and you either take a sip or dip your bread.</li>\r\n	<li>People then return to their seat.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nIt''s not that scary. What is happening, however, is that we are playing out the "Last Supper," the last passover which Jesus celebrated, the night before he was sentenced to death on the cross. While the ceremony he was celebrating remembered the Israelites being rescued from Egypt even as the Egyptians were being killed, Jesus used the ceremony to show that he was rescuing his followers from Sin, and would die in the process.\r\n\r\nIf you want to know more, please contact our rector', 'How do you do communion?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'how-do-you-do-communion', '', '', '2010-09-25 21:10:12', '2010-09-25 21:10:12', '', 0, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch.com/?p=79', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(80, 1, '2010-09-22 18:42:16', '2010-09-22 18:42:16', 'We practice what is called ''Open Communion.'' Basically we figure you''re an adult, and know that this is a solemn ceremony memorializing the sacrifice that Jesus made on our behalf. For that reason, both we and <a href="http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=1%20Corinthians%2011:27-29&amp;version=NLT">Scripture</a> suggest you not take it lightly, but we do encourage <em>all</em> baptised Christians (regardless of denomination) to join.  Typically, we suggest that younger children should be confirmed (usually around the age of 11 or 12) before actually taking the elements, but again, we trust you to make that decision.\n\nIf for any reason you are not comfortable taking communion, please come forward anyway to receive a blessing. If you are concerned about catching anything, you needn''t - our priest uses rubbing alcohol to clean his hands before serving, and the vessels are thoroughly washed after every service.  Finally, if you would prefer, a separate cup for continction (dipping) is available.\n\n<em><em>So, what is communion?</em></em> If you were observing it like an anthropologist, this is what you''d see:\n<ol>\n	<li>The Priest pours a cup of wine and prays over a piece of bread.</li>\n	<li>Everybody in the church will get out of their seats (by rows), and stand in line until there is space available to kneel at the altar.</li>\n	<li>When you get to the altar, if you do NOT want to take the elements, simply cross your hands over your chest, and the priest will give you a blessing. You can simply leave at this point.</li>\n	<li>Those receiving communion will hold their hand out for the bread, which the priest will place on the hand. One can either eat the bread or wait until the cup comes and dip it.</li>\n	<li>The cup of wine is then brought, and you either take a sip or dip your bread.</li>\n	<li>People then return to their seat.</li>\n</ol>\nIt''s not that scary. What is happening, however, is that we are playing out the "Last Supper," the last passover which Jesus celebrated, the night before he was sentenced to death on the cross. While the ceremony he was celebrating remembered the Israelites being rescued from Egypt even as the Egyptians were being killed, Jesus used the ceremony to show that he was', 'How do you do communion?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '79-revision', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:42:16', '2010-09-22 18:42:16', '', 79, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch.com/archives/80', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
