(132, 1, '2010-09-23 16:22:55', '2010-09-23 16:22:55', 'Sr. Warden: Wanda Pritekel\r\n\r\n<strong>Terms Expiring in 2011\r\n</strong>Patti Gile (Registrar)\r\nJillian Roebuck\r\n\r\n<strong>Terms Expiring in 2012\r\n</strong>Steve Cochran\r\nJohn Eastman\r\nCarolyn Kleinsmith\r\nChris Maggio\r\nAlexander Owusu-Gwayu\r\nKay Skelton\r\nMichael Ueltzen', 'Vestry', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'vestry', '', '', '2010-09-23 17:28:20', '2010-09-23 17:28:20', '', 30, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(117, 1, '2010-09-22 18:44:42', '2010-09-22 18:44:42', 'Mostly, you just show up :) We don''t carry badges that say "Episcopal" and "Other."\r\n\r\nBeyond that, if you officially want to be an Episcopalian, you must either be baptised or transfer from another church, and be "received" by the Bishop during his yearly visit. For details, please contact the church at (703)327-4060.', 'How do I join?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '81-revision-2', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:44:42', '2010-09-22 18:44:42', '', 81, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch/archives/117', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(118, 1, '2010-09-22 18:42:49', '2010-09-22 18:42:49', 'We practice what is called ''Open Communion.'' Basically we figure you''re an adult, and know that this is a solemn ceremony memorializing the sacrifice that Jesus made on our behalf. For that reason, both we and <a href="http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=1%20Corinthians%2011:27-29&amp;version=NLT">Scripture</a> suggest you not take it lightly, but we do encourage <em>all</em> baptised Christians (regardless of denomination) to join.  Typically, we suggest that younger children should be confirmed (usually around the age of 11 or 12) before actually taking the elements, but again, we trust you to make that decision.\r\n\r\nIf for any reason you are not comfortable taking communion, please come forward anyway to receive a blessing. If you are concerned about catching anything, you needn''t - our priest uses rubbing alcohol to clean his hands before serving, and the vessels are thoroughly washed after every service.  Finally, if you would prefer, a separate cup for continction (dipping) is available.\r\n\r\n<em><em>So, what is communion?</em></em> If you were observing it like an anthropologist, this is what you''d see:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The Priest pours a cup of wine and prays over a piece of bread.</li>\r\n	<li>Everybody in the church will get out of their seats (by rows), and stand in line until there is space available to kneel at the altar.</li>\r\n	<li>When you get to the altar, if you do NOT want to take the elements, simply cross your hands over your chest, and the priest will give you a blessing. You can simply leave at this point.</li>\r\n	<li>Those receiving communion will hold their hand out for the bread, which the priest will place on the hand. One can either eat the bread or wait until the cup comes and dip it.</li>\r\n	<li>The cup of wine is then brought, and you either take a sip or dip your bread.</li>\r\n	<li>People then return to their seat.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nIt''s not that scary. What is happening, however, is that we are playing out the "Last Supper," the last passover which Jesus celebrated, the night before he was sentenced to death on the cross. While the ceremony he was celebrating remembered the Israelites being rescued from Egypt even as the Egyptians were being killed, Jesus used the ceremony to show that he was rescuing his followers from Sin, and would die in the process.\r\n\r\nIf you want to know more, please contact our rector', 'How do you do communion?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '79-revision-2', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:42:49', '2010-09-22 18:42:49', '', 79, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch/archives/118', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(119, 1, '2010-09-22 18:28:56', '2010-09-22 18:28:56', 'Clothes. We definately recommend clothes at our services. :)\r\n\r\nBeyond that, Church of Our Redeemer is not a stuffy place. We don''t wear hats, and only a few people wear suits. Our rector and the people serving up front wear robes, but only in the service.  We''re not going to judge you by what you wear.\r\n\r\nThat said, some people would like to know how "everybody else dresses." If it''s helpful to say, ''business casual,'' then go with that answer.', 'What should I wear?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '77-revision-2', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:28:56', '2010-09-22 18:28:56', '', 77, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch/archives/119', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(120, 1, '2010-09-22 18:26:31', '2010-09-22 18:26:31', 'Church of Our Redeemer conducts services according the (episcopal) <em>1979 Book of Common Prayer</em> in a ''low church'' style. If you grew up in an Anglican tradition, the forms will be familiar.  If like many of us in the church, however, you didn''t, here''s a few hints.\r\n\r\n1.The entire service is printed in the bulletin each week, and for the most part, you just follow along. Whenever the bulletin says, ''People,'' you read off what it says :)\r\n\r\n2. The order of service usually compromises the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>an opening prayer and song</li>\r\n	<li>readings from the Old Testament, the Psalms, the Epistles, and a reading from the Gospels (during which we typically stand)</li>\r\n	<li>a sermon,usually about 20 minutes or so</li>\r\n	<li>a time of creedal affirmation and prayer</li>\r\n	<li>a time of "Peace" in which we greet one another</li>\r\n	<li>a time of Eucharist (Communion) in which we celebrate the Lord''s Last Supper</li>\r\n	<li>and coffee hour, in which we fellowship with our church</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n3. What if I get lost in the service?\r\n\r\nDon''t worry, we all do. Just peek over at your neighbor, and they''ll help you out.', 'What should I expect in a service at Church of Our Redeemer?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '74-revision-3', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:26:31', '2010-09-22 18:26:31', '', 74, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch/archives/120', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(121, 1, '2010-09-22 18:19:30', '2010-09-22 18:19:30', 'There is music and a choir at the 10am service. We choose a wide variety of modern and classical music from <em>The Hymnal 1982, Renew</em>, and<em> Lift Every Voice and Sing</em>.We have enough old Baptists in our congregation to ensure that a wide variety of the classics get sung.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, we present a children''s christmas concert during Advent.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to join the choir, you are invited to show up at practice on Thursday nights at 7:30.', 'What do you do for music?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '68-revision-5', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:19:30', '2010-09-22 18:19:30', '', 68, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch/archives/121', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(122, 1, '2010-09-22 18:13:33', '2010-09-22 18:13:33', 'Indeed we do!\r\n\r\nWomen meet weekly on Wednesday mornings at 9:30am in the fellowship hall.\r\n\r\nMen meet monthly on the 2nd Sunday of each month. Contact Michael Hollinger (mcholl@yahoo.com) for an electronic copy of the bible study that we will discuss for the upcoming month. We meet in the Gateway room shorty after the service (but not so shortly that we don''t get a bite or two from coffee hour)\r\n\r\nWednesday evenings are a "co-ed" Bible Study, meeting in the fellowship hall at 7pm.\r\n\r\nAdditional opportunities for discipleship, fellowship, and study are held throughout the year, and are advertised in the announcements.', 'Do you have programs for adults?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '66-revision-2', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:13:33', '2010-09-22 18:13:33', '', 66, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch/archives/122', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(123, 1, '2010-09-22 18:09:43', '2010-09-22 18:09:43', 'In addition to the nursery, we provide Sunday School for children ages 3 through 12th grade, during the 10am service only.\r\n\r\nChildren ages 3 - 5 are "Lambs" and meet in the fellowship hall, in the section furthest to the left.\r\nChildren in 1st through 3rd grade are "Lions" and meet in the fellowship hall, in the middle section.\r\nChildren in 4th through 6th grade meet in the upstairs office, visible from the fellowship hall.\r\nHigh Schoolers meet in the "Gateway Room," down the hall from the fellowship hall.\r\n\r\nFor questions regarding curriculum, please contact the church office.', 'Do you have programs for my child? for my teenager?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '62-revision-3', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:09:43', '2010-09-22 18:09:43', '', 62, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch/archives/123', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(124, 1, '2010-09-22 18:10:16', '2010-09-22 18:10:16', 'Yes, we provide a free-of-charge nursery using paid staff during the 10am service. There is no child care during the 8am service.\r\n\r\nYou can expect that your infant - 3 year old will be cared for by a competent care giver in a low worker-to-child ratio environment. Please come downstairs and turn into the hallway that leads away from the fellowship hall, through the open door. The nursery will be the first room on the right and has a dutch (half) door with a clear glass paned window and a wide assortment of toys.\r\n\r\nOlder children have Sunday School available, and will join us for Eucharist towards the end of the service. Children in the nursery will remain in the nursery until the parent who dropped them off retrieves them.\r\n\r\nFor the benefit of all children, we ask that if your child has had a fever or significant nasal discharge in the last 24 hours, please do NOT bring them to nursery.  If your child''s feeding time is during the service, please bring a bottle.', 'Do you have childcare?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '59-revision-4', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:10:16', '2010-09-22 18:10:16', '', 59, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch/archives/124', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(125, 1, '2010-09-22 18:00:38', '2010-09-22 18:00:38', 'OUR MISSION:\r\n\r\nTo serve God, to exalt Jesus Christ our Lord and Savior, to proclaim His Word.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nSTATEMENT OF FAITH:\r\n\r\nWe affirm our belief in historic Christianity as revealed in the Scriptures and\r\nsummarized in the three Creeds (the <a href=''http://www.creeds.net/ancient/apostles.htm''>Apostles</a>, the <a href=''http://www.creeds.net/ancient/nicene.htm''>Nicene</a>, and the <a href=''http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Athanasian_Creed''>Athanasian</a>)\r\nand the <a href=''http://anglicansonline.org/basics/thirty-nine_articles.html''>Thirty-Nine Articles</a>. We recognize the need to proclaim and to reaffirm\r\nthe following beliefs:\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nARTICLE 1 - The Holy Trinity\r\n\r\nThe mystery of the Holy Trinity, namely, that the one God exists eternally in\r\nthe three persons: Father, Son and Holy Spirit; and has so revealed himself to\r\nus in the Gospel.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nARTICLE II - The Lord Jesus Christ\r\n\r\nThe full deity and full humanity of our Lord Jesus Christ, God Incarnate, who\r\nby reason of his birth of the Virgin Mary, sinless life, atoning death, bodily\r\nresurrection, glorious ascension and triumphant reign, is the only Mediator\r\nbetween God and man.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nARTICLE III - The Holy Scriptures\r\n\r\nThe trustworthiness of the canonical books of the Old and New Testaments as\r\n“God’s Word written,” which contain all things necessary for salvation, teach\r\nGod’s will for his world, and have supreme authority for faith, life and the\r\ncontinuous renewal and reform of the Church.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nARTICLE IV - Justification and Sanctification\r\n\r\nThe justification of the repenting and believing sinner as God’s gracious act\r\nof declaring him righteous on the ground of the reconciling death of Christ,\r\nwho suffered in our place and rose again for us; and sanctification as the\r\ngracious continuing activity of the Holy Spirit in the justified believer,\r\nperfecting his repentance, nurturing the new life implanted within him,\r\ntransforming him into Christ’s image, and enabling him to do good works in the\r\nworld.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nARTICLE V - The Christian Church\r\n\r\nThe Church as the Body of Christ, whose members belong to the new humanity, are\r\ncalled to live in the world in the power of the Spirit, worshiping God,\r\nconfessing his truth, proclaiming Christ, supporting one another in love and\r\ngiving themselves in sacrificial service to those in need.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nARTICLE VI - Spiritual Gifts and Ministry\r\n\r\nThe calling of all Christians to exercise their God-given gifts in ministry,\r\nand to work, witness, and suffer for Christ; together with the particular\r\ncalling of ordained ministers, who, by preaching, teaching and pastoral care,\r\nare to equip God’s people for his service, and to present them mature in\r\nChrist.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nARTICLE VII - The Gospel Sacraments\r\n\r\nThe sacraments of Baptism and Holy Communion as “visible words” which proclaim\r\nthe Gospel, and are means of grace by which faith is quickened and\r\nstrengthened.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIn particular, the significance of the Lord’s Supper as a communion in the Body\r\nand Blood of Christ, who offers himself to us in the action of this sacrament,\r\nso that by faith we may feed on him in our hearts and offer ourselves to him in\r\ngratitude for our salvation through his cross; Also, the openness of the Lord’s\r\nTable as the place where all baptized believers, being one in Christ, are free\r\nto celebrate their common salvation in the Lord, and to express their common\r\ndevotion to his person and his service.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nARTICLE VIII - The Return of Christ\r\n\r\nThe personal return in glory of our Lord Jesus Christ at the end of this age\r\nfor the resurrection of the dead, some to life, some to condemnation, for the\r\nglorification of his Church, and for the renewal of the whole creation.', 'What do you believe?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '56-revision-3', '', '', '2010-09-22 18:00:38', '2010-09-22 18:00:38', '', 56, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch/archives/125', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(126, 1, '2010-09-22 17:56:46', '2010-09-22 17:56:46', 'Save the date. You know you''ll come.', 'Shrinemont Retreat – November 12th – 14th, 2010', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '52-revision-3', '', '', '2010-09-22 17:56:46', '2010-09-22 17:56:46', '', 52, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch/archives/126', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(127, 1, '2010-09-22 17:55:44', '2010-09-22 17:55:44', 'We need volunteers to man the moonbounce, greet visitors, paint faces, and generally be available. For more information, contact Lucia Benedetto and sign up during coffee hour.', 'Aldie Day is October 18th', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '50-revision-2', '', '', '2010-09-22 17:55:44', '2010-09-22 17:55:44', '', 50, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch/archives/127', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(128, 1, '2010-09-22 17:56:38', '2010-09-22 17:56:38', 'Part of being disciple is learning the discipline of service. If you''re unsure of how to start, why not start by being an usher?\r\n\r\nBeing an usher requires no preparation or commitment outside of the service, and yet it is the first contact that most members will have as they join the church. Responsibilities boil down to greeting people with the joy you already have, giving them a bulletin, and bringing up the communion elements after announcements.  It''s easy but important. \r\n\r\nIf you''re ready to sign up, please contact John Sheehan at (703)327-4060.', 'We need ushers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '47-revision-4', '', '', '2010-09-22 17:56:38', '2010-09-22 17:56:38', '', 47, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch/archives/128', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(129, 1, '2010-09-22 17:51:13', '2010-09-22 17:51:13', 'God loves you. Want to know more? Visit <a href="http://aldie-alpha.com">http://aldie-alpha.com</a> and join us every Wednesday night at 7pm beginning September 22, 2010.', 'Alpha is Coming', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '45-revision-2', '', '', '2010-09-22 17:51:13', '2010-09-22 17:51:13', '', 45, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch/archives/129', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
