(220, 238, 249); }.thumbnailsTable { width: 625px; border: 1px solid black; border-spacing: 1px 10px; -moz-border-radius: 8px 8px 8px 8px; -moz-box-shadow: 1px 2px 5px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5); }.thumbnailsTitle { color: rgb(128, 128, 128); }.thumbnailContainer { padding: 15px 1px 1px; width: 205px; text-align: center; vertical-align: bottom; }.thumbnailBox { display: inline-block; padding: 5px; border: 2px solid rgb(255, 255, 255); font-weight: bold; -moz-border-radius: 8px 8px 8px 8px; }.thumbnailLink { padding: 1px; font-family: tahoma,helvetica,arial,sans-serif; font-size: 12px; width: 205px; text-align: center; vertical-align: top; }.thumbnailImg { -moz-border-radius: 8px 8px 8px 8px; }.fontT1 { font-family: arial,sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 16px; }.fontT2 { font-family: arial,sans-serif; font-size: 11px; line-height: 13px; }.fontT3 { font-family: arial,sans-serif; font-size: 10px; line-height: 12px; }.fontH1 { font-family: arial,sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 18px; }.fontBold { font-weight: bold; }.fontMedGray { color: rgb(119, 119, 119); }.fontDarkGray { color: rgb(34, 34, 34); }.colorK2 { border-top: 2px dotted rgb(216, 216, 216) ! important; }.colorK3 { border-color: rgb(193, 204, 211) ! important; }.colorWhite { background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); }.fontT0 { font-family: arial,sans-serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 17px; }.fontLink { color: rgb(0, 129, 194); }.textLink { cursor: pointer; } -->Since we began this Bible study, we’ve been making an assumption. It isn’t a bad assumption, but it is still one worth investigating. What we’ve been assuming is this – that we find Truth in the Bible.  After all, if we didn’t, then Bible Study would be no different than studying Shakespeare or Stephen King or Civil War History.  But why is that we think that (a) we can find Truth in the Scriptures and the (b) we believe that Scripture is in fact truth? This month, I’d like to ask one big question:\n<div id="cg_msg_content">\n<blockquote>\n<div>\n<div>\n<ol>\n	<li>Why do we believe what we believe?</li>\n</ol>\nWe evaluate all sorts of claims to Truth every day. We do it so naturally that we often don’t think about how we do it.\n\nWe believe, for instance, that the world is round, and not flat.  But why? You <em>could</em> prove this experientially – by flying around the world. You <em>could</em> prove this logically by observing a ship sailing away as it disappears beneath the horizon. You <em>could </em>study Genesis 1 and contemplate the “dome” of the heavens against which the birds fly or note that Job speaks of God hanging the earth upon nothingness in the heavens. Or, you <em>could</em> simply appeal to the fact that “everybody knows” the world is round.  Each of these arguments represent a different path to arriving at Truth that is not dependent on the feelings or opinions of the person making the argument.\n\nAt the risk of plagiarizing from John Wesley (which I am doing), I want to suggest four words to summarize these “sources of authority:”  Scripture, Tradition, Reason, and Experience.  Whenever we make a theological argument, we will be appealing to one or more of these four categories – and if we’re not, we’re just spouting an opinion or a feeling.\n\nNow, why is that important?  Imagine two people talking. One says, “There is a God.” The other says, “No there isn’t.”  Absent Scripture, Tradition, Reason, or Experience, the conversation quickly resembles something Jonathan and Rachel fill their conversations with.\n\nThis month, I want to tackle the book of 2 Timothy, and in doing so, examine why we study Scripture, go to church, and frankly, why we believe what we believe.\n\nBefore we go any further, please take the fifteen minutes or so that it will take to simply read the book.  We will come back to parts, but please first just read it in its entirety.\n\nWelcome back!  You did read it, right?  Let’s start by just doing some basic recall.\n<ol>\n	<li>Who wrote this book, and to whom 	was it written?</li>\n	<li>Who are Eunice and Lois?</li>\n	<li>Of what should Timothy not be 	ashamed?</li>\n	<li>To what three jobs does Paul 	compare the Christian life in chapter 2?</li>\n	<li>What is Paul’s advice about 	“quarrelling with words”?</li>\n	<li>What will people be like in “the 	last days?”</li>\n	<li>What four things is all Scripture 	“profitable” for?</li>\n	<li>What kinds of teachers will people 	gather to themselves in “the last days?”</li>\n</ol>\nNotice in each of those questions, I’m not asking you to interpret or judge – I’m just sort of checking your recall.  If these questions are hard to answer, go back and re-read it. Again – it’s a short book.\n\nNow, let’s ask are next question:\n<ol>\n	<li>What is this book about?</li>\n</ol>\nIdeally, pick just a few words or one verse that sums up what Paul is trying to convey.  As a general hint, I’d suggest you look more at the beginning of the book (Chapter 1) moreso than the end.\n\nNow, let me also suggest to you that even though there are a lot of names in this book, most of them don’t really matter.  Let me take a moment and fill some details that might be helpful.\n<ol type="a">\n	<li>Obviously, Paul is the author.  	You probably also noticed that he mentioned he was “suffering for 	the Gospel,” and “in chains.”  Clues like these help us to 	really nail down some things about when this book was written, and 	there is just about universal agreement by scholars about the 	context.  We know historically that Paul was a great missionary – 	he started a lot of churches – and as a result got a lot of 	religious leaders rather angry at him. We know from the Book of Acts 	(written by Paul’s companion Luke that Paul mentions in Chapter 4) 	that eventually he was thrown into prison for several years, until 	eventually he was beheaded. The general tone of the book suggests 	this was probably Paul’s last letter, shortly before his 	execution.</li>\n	<li>Timothy is the person to whom Paul 	is writing. From Chapter 1, we know that his mother (Eunice) and his 	grandmother (Lois) were both Christians, and from other letters we 	know that Paul asked Timothy to pastor one of the churches that Paul 	started – probably the one in Ephesus, a large city on the Turkish 	coast. An analogy in today’s terms might be like Franklin Graham – 	son of Billy Graham – pastoring a church in a city like New York.</li>\n</ol>\n--  The lesser characters --\n<ol type="a">\n	<li>Lois &amp; Eunice, as we said, are 	Timothy’s grandmother and mother. They just show the history.</li>\n	<li>Jannes &amp; Jambres are the names 	traditionally given to the magicians that Moses encountered when 	trying to get Pharaoh to  “let my people go.”  If you remember 	the scene where Yul Brenner throws his rod on the ground and it 	turns into a snake, then some Egyptian magicians do the same thing, 	but then Moses’ snake eats up the other snakes, then you are 	remembering Jannes &amp; Jambres.</li>\n	<li>Luke is the author of the Book of 	Luke &amp; Acts, and as we see here, a guy who travels with Paul.</li>\n	<li>Mark (called John Mark) is a young 	guy who had at one point travelled with Paul but then who “chickened 	out” and left. Paul was ticked, but you’ll notice here he’s 	now forgiven him.</li>\n</ol>\nAll of that’s fun to know, but not really central, right?  The main point of this book, as I see it, can be summarized in two words: “Hold On!”  Why?\n<ol type="a">\n	<li>There are a lot of people who want 	to convince you that what they believe is right.</li>\n	<li>Much of what people believe is 	what they <em>want</em> to believe rather than established truth.</li>\n	<li>What you already know <em>is</em> true, &amp; we know that from Scripture, Tradition, Reason, &amp; 	Experience, so…</li>\n	<li>Hold On!</li>\n</ol>\nNotice that there is a context – Paul is telling Timothy, “Hold on to what you know.”  There was a fixed point in time for that exact message from Paul to Timothy. Notice also that the same bit of advice is relevant for us today.  That’s how Bible Study works. See what was being said then; See what we share in common today; See what advice it holds for us today.\n\nSo, let’s put all of this together:\n\n<em>The World</em>\n<ol>\n	<li>In Chapters 3 &amp; 4, what does 	Paul say the world will be like?</li>\n	<li>What does it mean to “scoff at 	God?”</li>\n	<li>What does it mean to say that 	people have “itching ears?”</li>\n	<li>Is this the world we live in 	today?</li>\n</ol>\n<em>How to evaluate Truth - Tradition</em>\n<ol>\n	<li>What kinds of things did Timothy 	learn from his mother &amp; grandmother?</li>\n	<li>Did Timothy get to choose what 	his mother &amp; grandmother would be like?</li>\n	<li>What can be dangerous about 	relying on Tradition to determine if something is or isn’t true?</li>\n</ol>\n<em>How to evaluate Truth – Reason</em>\n<ol>\n	<li>What is the danger of relying 	strictly on building good sounding arguments? (Hint: Look at 2 Tim 	2: 14 – 18; 3: 5 – 7; Isa 55: 8 – 9)</li>\n	<li>Does that mean we should never try 	use logic to figure out truth? (Hint: 2 Tim 2:20)</li>\n	<li>How do you know when  to rely on 	reason?</li>\n</ol>\n<em>How to evaluate Truth - Experience</em>\n<ol>\n	<li>In 2 Tim 3:10, Paul starts talking 	about his life. What kinds of things did Paul see in his life?</li>\n	<li>Why is it that  persecutions and 	sufferings would make Paul <em>more</em> convinced of the truth of 	Jesus Christ?</li>\n	<li>What is the danger in relying 	strictly on your own experience?</li>\n</ol>\nSo, Tradition, Reason, and Experience all have their upsides and their downsides, right?  What does that leave? Scripture!  Let’s look at 3:16.  Again,\n<ol>\n	<li>What is Scripture good for? What 	does it do?</li>\n	<li>Why is it important that Scripture 	doesn’t change from generation to generation?</li>\n</ol>\nThink about the U.S. Constitution for a minute. Debates asides about how the Constitution is interpreted and whether or not the Supreme Court should or should not interpret it, what is the benefit of having a written set of rules to guide government? Imagine, for instance, that a very popular president, having served two terms, could still garner 95% of the vote to be declared “President-for-life.”  Even if 95% of the people want him to stay on, what would be the danger? Or, imagine that 95% of the people decided that Congress should make a law that says for instance, that people should not be allowed to wear a burqha<a rel="nofollow" name="sdfootnote1anc" href="http://us.mg2.mail.yahoo.com/dc/blank.html?bn=504.5&amp;.intl=us&amp;.lang=en-US#sdfootnote1sym"><sup>1</sup></a>.  What safeguards in the Constitution prohibit that? Why is it important that a decision made 200 years ago should still be examined? I bring these questions up mainly to have you think about the “check” that a written document has.\n\nThere is a lot more to talk about in regards to the “perfection” of Scripture, and we are bound to talk about these things – but I just wanted to skim the surface at first to get you thinking about these things.  We’ll talk more on Sunday.  See you then!\n<div id="sdfootnote1">\n\n<a rel="nofollow" name="sdfootnote1sym" href="http://us.mg2.mail.yahoo.com/dc/blank.html?bn=504.5&amp;.intl=us&amp;.lang=en-US#sdfootnote1anc">1</a> And this *is* happening right now in both France and Belgium.\n\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></blockquote>\n</div>', '#6 - Evaluating Claims of Truth', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '303-revision', '', '', '2010-10-30 16:24:58', '2010-10-30 21:24:58', '', 303, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch/archives/304', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(305, 1, '2010-10-30 17:19:52', '2010-10-30 22:19:52', '<h2 style="text-align: center;">What is a Saint?</h2>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: center;">Luke 6:20-31</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">A Sermon delivered bt the Rev. John Thomas Sheehan</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">All Saint’s Day</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">October 31, 2010</p>\r\nA question I ask myself about this time every year is, <strong>"What is a saint?"</strong> There are a couple ways to answer the question. The first, and the most obvious given that we are in the middle of the football season, is that a Saint is a member of the football team located in New Orleans. Of course, this is not the answer I’m looking for.\r\n\r\nOthers will look at the, Catholic definition for a saint:\r\n\r\n"someone who has passed away who was a strong Christian through their lives,\r\n\r\nand who had some miracle attributed to them after their death."\r\n\r\nEven though the Catholic Church is rigorous with their desire for proof for miracles, I’m not sure miracles play a major role in the qualifications for sainthood.\r\n\r\nSo, I guess I’ll stick with the Prayer Book definition: (862) What is the communion of saints?\r\n\r\n"The communion of saints is the whole family of God, the living and the dead, those whom we love\r\n\r\nand those whom we hurt, bound together in Christ by sacrament, prayer, and praise."\r\n\r\nThe early Protestants did a good job of democratizing our understanding of sainthood. They said that there aren’t different levels of Christianity. There aren’t normal Christians and Super Christians. Instead, once we have accepted Christ, we are all saved and therefore, we are all saints. A saint isn’t a perfect person, a saint is a forgiven sinner. And today, as we celebrate All Saints Day, we remember the saints who have gone before us,\r\n\r\nguiding our path with their witness, and we also look at our own calling as saints.\r\n\r\nWhat are the qualifications for Sainthood? Well, since the concept of saint has been brought to the masses, since we recognize that all of us are saints, we might choose to allow ourselves the easy way out. We might allow ourselves to figure that since we’ve been saved, since we’ve prayed the prayer, We are where we need to be and we don’t need to do much else. If we allow ourselves to live this way, I believe that we are making a mistake. You see, I don’t think that it’s an accident that the scripture for All Saints Day comes from Luke 6.\r\n\r\nHere Jesus is describing what it is he calls us to be as his followers. Jesus is telling us what the qualifications for a saint are. Jesus is reminding us of what it means to be a child of God. There’s nothing in here about praying a prayer or accepting Jesus into your heart. No, Jesus is calling us to something deeper and more meaningful.\r\n\r\nJesus is calling us to faith and faithfulness.\r\n\r\nHere, in Luke 6, we have a description of what a child of God looks like; here we have the qualifications if we are interested in taking that on in our lives.\r\n\r\nI think it’s important, with our protestant theology, to realize that this description, that these qualifications, aren’t just for a few, they are for all saints, they are for all Christians. And so when we look at them we find ourselves wanting:\r\n\r\n?\r\n\r\nBlessed are you who are poor, for yours is the kingdom of God.\r\n\r\nBlessed are you who hunger now, for you will be satisfied.\r\n\r\nBlessed are you who weep now, for you will laugh.\r\n\r\nBlessed are you when people hate you, when they exclude you,\r\n\r\ninsult you and reject your name as evil, because of the Son of Man.\r\n\r\nRejoice in that day and leap for joy, because great is your reward in heaven.\r\n\r\nLove your enemies, do good to those who hate you,\r\n\r\nbless those who curse you, pray for those who mistreat you.\r\n\r\nIf someone strikes you on one cheek, turn to him the other also.\r\n\r\nIf someone takes your cloak, do not stop him from taking your tunic.\r\n\r\nGive to everyone who asks you, and if anyone takes what belongs to you, do not demand it back.\r\n\r\nDo to others as you would have them do to you.\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\nI squirm when I read these verses. First of all there’s the whole part about hungering and weeping and being poor. It seems that God wants his children to be poor. This doesn’t match what I’ve been taught about Christianity. Doesn’t God want the best for me? Well, yes, but the best doesn’t necessarily have to do with money.\r\n\r\nIt’ much easier to read Matthews sermon where Jesus talks about being poor in spirit and hungering for righteousness. And I know that Jesus taught using those words some times. But other times, Jesus taught\r\n\r\nusing these words and I find them a bit harder to accept. Being poor, weeping, hungering, these are good things?\r\n\r\nWell, God makes promises to those who endure these things, because he honors people who go through them.\r\n\r\nIn Jesus’ eyes, being a saint is about suffering for God. Again, I squirm when I read this. I’m not comfortable with this message, but that is what it is. This is not the Christianity that I thought I understood. There was nothing in it about suffering. Oh, there are Christians in other parts of the world who have to suffer for their faith, there are Christians in the past who were persecuted because of what they believed, and we can look up to these martyrs, but we also thank God that we don’t have to deal with the things they deal with.\r\n\r\nAnd then we come to this passage, telling us that God blesses those who are persecuted, telling us that the riches the world has to offer aren’t all they’re cracked up to be, telling us that suffering for the sake of Christ is actually a good thing.\r\n\r\nJesus didn’t just preach this, he lived it. Jesus lived a life of suffering. Jesus could have come to earth as a king. Jesus could have ruled from a palace with many servants. But he chose the life of a homeless man during his three year ministry. He chose to travel from town to town and he learn to rely on those around him to meet his needs. He could encourage his disciples to ask God for their daily bread because that is the way he lived. So he wasn’t looking down at the poor when he told them they would be blessed. He wasn’t giving platitudes from on high. He was speaking from among them. Jesus knew what hunger was, He knew what it was to weep. These were real things to him. And Jesus knew what it meant to suffer for his message. Because, he suffered in the ultimate way as he headed to the cross. These things were real to him. This is the way he lived. And he told his disciples, and I believe, he is telling us as well, that this is the way the child of God is to live.\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>Have you turned your life over to Jesus? Terrific! Did you pray a prayer asking Jesus into your heart? Wonderful! OK now, find a way to start living it. Start being a saint, which we all are, which means that we are called to a difficult life. It means that life can and often will be difficult. It means a life of sacrifice. It means that you can’t always put your own needs first.\r\n\r\nWe often forget about the work involved in being a saint, and yet, there it is.\r\n\r\nThere aren’t levels of Christianity. There aren’t normal Christians and then Super Christians who really have to work at it. We are all called to work at it in our own way in our own lives.\r\n\r\nThink back to those saints who have gone before. Think back to parents and grandparents, aunts an uncles, friends and neighbors, that truly lived the life. Think of the example that they have been to you. And remember how much they put into their faith. Remember how God came first in their lives. And know that if we want to truly honor them then we are called to the same life of sacrifice for our faith. And then we will find the same blessing in Jesus’ eyes that they found when we are willing to suffer for God.\r\n\r\nPaul tells us that we are surrounded by a great cloud of witnesses. He reminds us that we are not alone in our faith. We can remember those who have gone before, we know that there are children of God around the world today. He offers this comfort. But it is not only comfort. It is also encouragement for us to struggle on.\r\n\r\nSince we are surrounded by a great cloud of witnesses, we can struggle on in the faith. Since we have saints who have gone before us, Since we are standing on their shoulders, we cannot just sit back on our laurels and allow our faith to be simple and easy.\r\n\r\nSo let us seek to be the children of God that Jesus calls us to be. Let us seek to be the saints that Jesus calls us to be. It isn’t easy, but we’re in good company, and we have many saints who have gone before us cheering us on and encouraging us to move forward.\r\n\r\nLet us pray: Dear Heavenly Father, we give you thanks for all your saints throughout the ages, who have revealed your word in faithfulness and who have enabled the proclamation of your redeeming grace in Jesus the Christ to be passed on from generation to generation. Through the power of your Holy Spirit, inspire us and give us the courage to witness to the Gospel through our own lives, so that it might continue to nurture faith for generations to come. This we ask in Jesus’ holy name. Amen.', 'What is a Saint?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-is-a-saint', '', '', '2010-10-30 17:20:45', '2010-10-30 22:20:45', '', 0, 'http://doverknoll.com/aldiechurch/?p=305', 0, 'post', '', 0);
